content:
Salesforce uses certificates to ensure the security of your Service Cloud Voice contact center. If a certificate is about to expire, you'll receive an email to replace it with a new one. Service Cloud Voice supports certificates with up to 4,096-bit keys.

To create, edit, and manage certificates, Customize Application user permissions are required.

When creating a Voice contact center with Amazon Connect, Salesforce creates a connected app that integrates Amazon Connect with Salesforce using a certificate to authenticate users. When notified of an expiring certificate, check if it's for your contact center and provide a replacement.

Updating the certificate includes a brief period when single sign-on (SSO) is unavailable, so complete the update during low-traffic times.

To replace a certificate:

*   Check the expiration date in the Idp Certificate field.
*   Create a new self-signed certificate.
*   Replace the identity provider's certificate.
*   Update the connected app's certificate.
*   Upload the new metadata XML file to AWS.
*   Verify that your contact center is using the new certificate.
title: Managing Contact Center Certificates in Service Cloud
